BEGIN:VCALENDAR
PRODID:-//notapattern//calendar export 1.0//EN
VERSION:2.0
CALSCALE:GREGORIAN
METHOD:PUBLISH
X-WR-CALNAME:CATS: The Jellicle Ball
X-WR-TIMEZONE:America/New_York
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:981998
DTSTAMP:20260314T205230Z
DTSTART:20260318T233000Z
DTEND:20260319T021500Z
SUMMARY:CATS: The Jellicle Ball
LOCATION:Broadhurst Theatre, 235 West 44th Street, New York NY 10036
DESCRIPTION:<p>Come One, Come All &ndash; The Jellicle Cats are having a
  Ball. Based on T.S. Eliot&rsquo;s <em>Old Possum&rsquo;s Book of Practical
  Cats</em>, Andrew Lloyd Webber&rsquo;s worldwide phenomenon <em>CATS</em>
  is reimagined in a production that smashed records, won awards and left
  New York City purring. And now <em>CATS: The Jellicle Ball</em> ascends to
  Broadway in a kaleidoscope of glittering spectacle, iconic music and
  electrifying ballroom choreography that <em>The New York Times</em> calls
  &ldquo;a lightning strike that sets joy free!&rdquo;&nbsp;<br /><br
  />Broadway meets Runway in the fiercest event of the season, directed by
  Obie Award winners Zhailon Levingston and Bill Rauch, with choreography by
  Obie Award winners and New York City Ballroom icons Omari Wiles (House of
  NiNa Oricci) and Arturo Lyons (House of Miyake-Mugler). Don&rsquo;t miss
  this &ldquo;sexy celebration of love and resilience&rdquo; (<em>New York
  Daily News</em>) and &ldquo;the most exhilarating fun that can be had in
  the theater&rdquo; (<em>The Washington Post</em>).<br /><br />&ldquo;A
  lightning strike. <em>CATS: the Jellicle Ball</em> has managed a
  Grizabella return, reincarnating itself in fabulousness. It sets the joy
  free!&rdquo; &ndash;Jesse Green, <em>The New York Times<br /></em><br
  />&ldquo;Paris is purring. The fur flies in an absolutely fabulous
  reconception. Levingston and Rauch&rsquo;s vision fits <em>CATS: The
  Jellicle Ball</em> like a long sequined glove.&rdquo; &ndash;Adam Feldman,
  <em>Time Out New York</em><br /><br />&ldquo;This splashy, jaw-dropping
  reimagination of Andrew Lloyd Webber&rsquo;s crowd-pleasing <em>CATS</em>
  is the most exhilarating fun that can be had in a theater.&rdquo; &ndash;
  Naveen Kumar, <em>The Washington Post</em><br /><br />FIVE STARS - 
  &ldquo;A raucous success. The most fun you'll have at the theater.&rdquo;
  &ndash;Johnny Oleksinski, <em>The New York Post</em></p>
END:VEVENT
